00:47:33,200 --> 00:47:37,960
basically, users who had taken a day off, we were 
getting them to come back more at higher rates,  

564
00:47:37,960 --> 00:47:42,880
and so it made up for our losses in CURR. 
But effectively, what this meant is that,  

565
00:47:42,880 --> 00:47:47,840
why two streak freezes work better than one was, 
I don't know, sometimes people just need a little  

566
00:47:47,840 --> 00:47:52,440
bit more flexibility than one day. But again, 
the really interesting insight of this experiment  

567
00:47:52,440 --> 00:47:57,040
was that three streak freezes was actually no 
better than two streak freezes. And there were  

568
00:47:57,040 --> 00:48:00,680
two competing things here, and I think this is 
important if you're going to build a streak to  

569
00:48:00,680 --> 00:48:05,680
figure out what your flexibility mechanic is.
We were getting more users to return after  

570
00:48:05,680 --> 00:48:12,400
longer times away to an intact streak. But if 
you start taking three days off from any habit,  

571
00:48:12,400 --> 00:48:15,880
it's just going to be less likely that 
you return even four days later. And so,  

572
00:48:15,880 --> 00:48:21,120
we had these competing things where more users 
might be returning to a streak, but a lot of users  

573
00:48:21,120 --> 00:48:27,720
were also just not coming back, we were training 
them to take more time off. So, that flexibility,  

574
00:48:27,720 --> 00:48:33,240
what's the right amount of... We've again, this is 
another area we've run hundreds of experiments on,  

575
00:48:33,240 --> 00:48:41,120
what is the right amount of flexibility? 
And we are constantly surprised here. I  

576
00:48:41,120 --> 00:48:44,440
still don't have the answer for at every point 
in your streak journey how much flexibility you  

577
00:48:44,440 --> 00:48:50,440
need. One thing that I can say with certainty 
though is, give more flexibility when a user is  

578
00:48:50,440 --> 00:48:55,680
starting their streak. Again, one of our biggest 
streak freeze experiment wins... I feel like I'm  

579
00:48:55,680 --> 00:48:59,760
constantly saying this, one of our biggest 
wins, but they all were really, really big. 

580
00:48:59,760 --> 00:49:03,800
One of our biggest streak freeze wins was when 
you start a new streak, we give you two streak  

581
00:49:03,800 --> 00:49:07,560
freezes. And again, it's so funny to think back, 
it's like how are we not doing this to begin with?  

582
00:49:07,560 --> 00:49:14,280
But at the time, the streak freeze was an overly 
gamified mechanic, you had to buy them with gems,  

583
00:49:14,280 --> 00:49:21,800
that's our in-app currency, because we wanted 
the whole idea of this to feel like it was really  

584
00:49:21,800 --> 00:49:26,320
something you earned, that there was a little bit 
of pain to getting that streak freeze. And so,  

585
00:49:26,320 --> 00:49:29,600
we tested though, what if we just give 
users when they start off their streak  

586
00:49:29,600 --> 00:49:36,360
two streak freezes, and holy smokes to that win.
And it's sort of obvious now, in retrospect, but  

587
00:49:36,360 --> 00:49:42,480
if you have a one or a two or a three-day streak, 
it's really easy just to let it die and restart,  

588
00:49:42,480 --> 00:49:46,760
again, you need to get to seven days, what we've 
seen in the data, for it to really lock in. And  

589
00:49:46,760 --> 00:49:51,720
so, giving users more flexibility so that it's 
harder to lose their streak initially, and then  

590
00:49:51,720 --> 00:49:56,800
conversely, and this is what we keep learning, 
eventually, once people get on long streaks,  

591
00:49:56,800 --> 00:50:04,760
you don't want to give them as much flexibility. 
Because there's a lot of times where, yeah, users  

592
00:50:04,760 --> 00:50:09,400
don't... And I'm like this, I've got a 400-day 
streak. Note that that is a lot less time than  

593
00:50:09,400 --> 00:50:14,200
I've been at Duolingo, I have lost and restarted 
streaks a lot of times at my time at Duolingo. 

594
00:50:14,200 --> 00:50:19,120
But you start getting on long streaks, and you 
really care about this feature, you really care  

595
00:50:19,120 --> 00:50:23,800
about your streak. And most people, as long as 
you're not backpacking through, I don't know,  

596
00:50:24,480 --> 00:50:32,920
the back country of Utah, you'll be in a place 
where you can get service. And so, figuring out  

597
00:50:34,000 --> 00:50:39,560
who is the user that actually could use Duolingo, 
and not conditioning them to start taking days off  

598
00:50:39,560 --> 00:50:46,360
that they didn't otherwise need to do is important 
to figure out where that line is for your feature.

599
00:50:46,360 --> 00:50:51,160
This is fascinating. You can also buy a streak, 
right? With money. That's a feature, right?

